**JavaScript Counter Instructions:**

Here's how to create a basic JavaScript counter, broken down into steps and with explanation:

**1.  HTML Setup (index.html):**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>JavaScript Counter</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css"> <!-- Optional CSS for styling -->
</head>
<body>

  <h1>Counter</h1>

  <span id="count">0</span>  <!-- Display the count here -->

  <div class="buttons">
    <button id="increment">Increment</button>
    <button id="decrement">Decrement</button>
    <button id="reset">Reset</button>
  </div>

  <script src="script.js"></script>  <!-- Link to your JavaScript file -->
</body>
</html>
```

**Explanation:**

*   **`<!DOCTYPE html>`**:  Tells the browser it's an HTML5 document.
*   **`<html>`, `<head>`, `<title>`, `<body>`**:  Standard HTML structure.
*   **`<link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">`**: Links an external CSS file (optional) for styling the counter.  You'll need to create a `style.css` file if you want to use this.
*   **`<h1>Counter</h1>`**: A heading for your counter.
*   **`<span id="count">0</span>`**:  This is where the current count will be displayed.  The `id="count"` is *crucial* because your JavaScript will use this `id` to find this element. The initial value is set to 0.  Using a `<span>` is a good choice because it's an inline element and won't force a line break.
*   **`<div class="buttons">`**: A container for the buttons.  The `class="buttons"` allows you to style the buttons together easily in CSS.
*   **`<button id="increment">Increment</button>`**: A button to increase the counter.  `id="increment"` is used by JavaScript.
*   **`<button id="decrement">Decrement</button>`**: A button to decrease the counter. `id="decrement"` is used by JavaScript.
*   **`<button id="reset">Reset</button>`**: A button to reset the counter to 0.  `id="reset"` is used by JavaScript.
*   **`<script src="script.js"></script>`**:  This is the most important part.  It tells the browser to load and execute the JavaScript code in the `script.js` file.  Make sure this is placed *at the end* of the `<body>` so that the HTML elements are loaded *before* the JavaScript tries to find them.

